    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-03-05T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-03-05T13:00:00-05:00" n="124"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d124">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.51/2220: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-03-05T19:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 5, 1926—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>36. From Gilbert.<note n="26" xml:id="d124fn26">S. Parker Gilbert, agent general
                        for reparation payments.</note> As you will have noticed from my
                    confidential telegram to Governor Strong,<note n="27" xml:id="d124fn27">Not
                        printed.</note> I have been devoting considerable time and effort since my
                    return to question of German borrowings abroad and have had satisfactory
                    discussions with the new Finance Minister and with the Reichsbank. Am not yet
                    satisfied however that the Beratungsstelle is exercising an effective control
                    over borrowings of states and municipalities. To some extent this is due to
                    defects in the form of organization which make it difficult for it to resist
                    political pressure. Hope that situation can be corrected but pending further
                    developments I do not suggest any change in the Department’s letter about German
                    loans in American market.<note n="28" xml:id="d124fn28">See letter to Harris,
                        Forbes &amp; Co., Nov. 21, 1925, <ref target="frus1925v02#pg_186">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1925, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 186</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>For your confidential information. Believe special care should be taken regarding
                    proposed loans to Prussian State and Reichspost in view of possible difficulties
                    under article 248 of the Treaty of Versailles.<note n="29" xml:id="d124fn29"
                        >Malloy, <hi rend="italic">Treaties</hi>, 1910–1923, vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 3329, 3439.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
